03973nam a22005175i 9780773562202DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19901990xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1399978522  a97807735622027 a10.1515/97807735622022doi  a(DE-B1597)655034  a(OCoLC)1245679859  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPZ7.B6513bTo 1990eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a813/.541 aBoswell, Hazel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTown House, Country House :bRecollections of a Quebec Childhood /cHazel Boswell. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1990] 4c©1990  a1 online resource (152 p.) :b59 b&w line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tAt Home and at School in Quebec -- tAutumn Adventures -- tA Quebec Christmas -- tThe Snow Fort and the Sugar Bush -- tThe Log Drive -- tOff to the Seigneury -- tOn the Beach -- tThe Sawmill -- tThe Raft -- tAn Exciting End to the Summer0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe story begins in autumn 1872 with Julie's school days and takes us through Christmas and the building of a snow fort at the foot of the Citadel in Québec City. During Easter week there is the marvellous annual sleigh trip to the sugar bush near Montmorency where the children eat fresh maple syrup, cooled by being poured onto the snow. In early spring, Henri joins a log drive and sees a log jam freed by dynamite. Come summer, the family goes by river boat up the St Lawrence to their summer home near Pointe Platon on the Seigneury de Lotbinière, sixty kilometres north of Québec City. While on the family seigneury the children find an old-fashioned flat-bottomed boat which they name the Rancid Butter because of the smell it has before they clean and fix it. They visit their father's sawmill and take an exciting trip on a huge raft which had come down from Trois-Rivières in a storm. Summer is brought to a close with a thrilling climax during the return trip down the St-Lawrence. Town House, Country House will charm all who pick it up, whether young or old. For younger readers, the story is clear and wonderfully intriguing. For those of us who are not so young, it has a fine sense of rhythm and a story so enchanting as to make us almost forget, despite the rich and vivid detail of post-confederation Québec, that we are looking into history. Jean François Bélisle's line drawings, which accompany the text, are splendidly evocative of the mood and setting of Town House, Country House.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356220240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773562202423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773562202/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles